76561197986801491,Recommended,249950,20062616,"Posted: 29 December, 2015",all,Javin,"Fought a chicken... With chickens... 10/10.  Would chicken fight again.Spoilers follow.  You ahve been warned.If you've read my previous reviews, you'll see that I generally go by the ""50 cent rule"".  I want to enjoy a game for 50 cents per hour.  Thus, a $50 game should give me 100 hours of play time.This game cost me $7.  It took exactly 14 hours to play.  This is a win.Forge Quest is a dungeon crawler similar to Diablo, but with the ""cutesy"" voxel/8-bit looking graphics (just look at the screen shots).  At no point does the game try to take itself very seriously.  There are a few good tongue in cheek jokes, but I won't spoil those for you as the game is fairly short.It starts with you as a new want-to-be hero who has to complete the 4 training dungeons to become one in the eyes of the law.  Each dungeon is only 4 ""levels"" deep, but the levels are fairly large, and the pacing is pretty decent.  New creatures/monsters/dungeon designs pop up just as you start to get bored with the old ones.  The algorithms for generating these dungeons randomly is pretty impressive, as each dungeon ""type"" is completely different from the previous.After completing the 4 dungeons, you'll fight the boss.  For me, the whole process took 14 hours, but I can say I enjoyed all 14 of them.  For the price, it was well worth it.My only complaint would be that some of the abilities are not particularly well balanced.  As a mage, I was able to max out my ""chicken attack"" fairly early in the game (by the second dungeon).  After that, the whole game was just far too easy.  Spamming the chickens would wipe out ANY group of mobs.  Even the bosses stood no chance against my chickens' wrath.  It's also possible that there is a glitch with the chicken attack, as it seems like any attack done not using them had a CHANCE to drop some loot, but every mob killed by the chickens dropped TONS of loot.  Even summoned skeletons and baby spiders.  I had crazy powerful gear by the second dungeon because of this.I also ran into a glitched side ""quest"" that couldn't be completed, but it wasn't game breaking.This feels a lot like a first attempt by an indy dev who now has an engine that they could do a LOT with, but this game itself only had 4 dungeons, and maybe 4 side ""quests"".  The bulk of my 14 hours was spent just grinding my way through the dungeons.For $7, it's well worth it though, and you'll get quite a few chuckles on your way through.  For what the game consists of right now, that 14 hours is just about the right amount of time, and it's unlikely I'll be going for another play through, even with the randomized dungeons.I do hope to see more from this developer, though.  The game FEELS very good, and very solid.  The engine is a treat to look at, and the humor is enjoyable.  I hope to see a much larger, much more involved game created with this engine in the future."
